column1: Will Ashraf Ghani cease to be president of Afghanistan before 1 July 2017?
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit']
column11: Ghani became president of Afghanistan in 2014 as part of national unity government under a deal brokered by the US, but that deal is set to expire in September 2016 and tensions between rival factions have led to some calls for a change in the composition or form of the Afghan government (Washington Post, Yahoo! News, VOA News). In the event that Ghani reportedly disappears or flees the capital, GJI will observe a three week waiting period, at the end of which the question will close retroactively to the date of his disappearance or exodus. If Ghani returns in the interim, the question will remain open. Recommended Questions When will Pierre Nkurunziza cease to be president of Burundi? Will Bashar al-Assad cease to be President of Syria before 1 March 2017?

";More than 150 people died in last week's Kabul suicide blast, President Ashraf Ghani said as he opened multi-national talks on bringing peace. Previous estimates said 90 people were killed in the bombing, the country's deadliest militant attack since 2001. Mr Ghani's government has faced protests for failing to tackle the deteriorating security situation. He told the meeting it was time for the Taliban to embrace peace or "face the consequences". Representatives of 23 nations including the US and Pakistan, as well as the EU, Nato and the UN are attending the two-day meeting, which launches what is being called the Kabul Process for Peace and Security Co-operation. UK Ambassador Dominic Jermey said it was "an important marker for each and every country in the region to show its true support for Afghanistan's aspirations for peace". As it got under way a rocket struck a tennis court in the Indian diplomatic compound. Police said no-one was hurt." http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40170596 Did not sound like he was resigning. I've looked at the trends in Afghanistan. Ghani has strong support from the United States and the international community. Although the situation in Afghanistan is bad, the trends are not significantly worse than 1 year ago. Furthermore, Ghani is full Pashtun, meaning he has level of stable support although he is at adds with Abdullah Abdullah's faction as part of the overall power sharing agreement. Short of assassination Ghani will remain President in 2017.

I think the current average of 25% is a bit pessimistic. As per the Afghan constitution, Ghani is supposed to serve a 5-year term. He also appears to have recieved a clear (if somewhat disputed) majority of votes in the 2014 presidential election (http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2014/09/ashraf-ghani-declared-winner-afghan-poll-2014921133512174572.html) , making him as legitimate a head of government as anyone. As far as I know there isn't a legislative mechanism to oust him, so the plausible "Yes" results here would come from a coup, a Taliban takeover, or Ghani dying.

The next election is in 2019 and the current power-sharing deal is to cover only Abdullah's possible ascent to the Prime Minister role from his current executive position. Ashraf Ghani will cease to be President only when there's an election or a civil war, neither of which seems probable within the next ten months: outside powers are going to do whatever they can to prevent a civil war, and that's by its nature going to need the power-sharing agreement to hold, one way or another.
